Exercise 1

Data set HW6_ex1.txt contains two features: x and y. Plot functions y = x, y = 1.5x and y = 2x on the data. Implement and calculate root mean squared error (RMSE) for each of the functions. Describe in few sentences (or make an illustration) about what does RMSE measure? Which of the models describes data the best?

Solution:

The Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE) is a measure of how close a fitted line is to data points. The regression line predicts the average y value associated with a given x value.

To construct the RMSE first we need to determine the residuals. Residuals are the difference between the actual values and the predicted values. They can be positive or negative as the predicted value under or over estimates the actual value. Squaring the residuals, averaging the squares, and taking the square root gives us the RMSE.

The RMSE is thus the distance, on average, of a data point from the fitted line, measured along a vertical line.

If we plot the functions y = x, y = 1.5x and y = 2x, we can notice that y = 1.5x seems to describe the data the best since the line best describes the relationship between the dependent variable y and x.

library(data.table)
data_6 <- fread("C:/Users/Arsovska/Desktop/HW6_exercise1-txt.csv")

plot(y ~ x, data = data_6, main = "Scatterplot for x and y")

abline(0, 1, col = "red")
abline(0, 1.5, col = "blue")
abline(0, 2, col = "green")

legend("topleft", legend = c("y=x", "y=1.5x", "y=2x"), col = c("red", "blue", 
    "green"), lty = c("solid", "solid", "solid"), cex = 0.7)

To check this we need to calculate the value of the RMSE. There are several ways in which we can do this in R. For example we can calculate the RMSE for the model x=y using the library Metrics.

library(Metrics)
RMSEm1 <- rmse(data_6$y, data_6$x)
RMSEm1
## [1] 4.274423

If we choose not the use the built in function in R, we just need to find the average sum of the squared residuals between the predicted and the actual values and then find the square root of this value.

res = data_6$y - data_6$x
RMSE1 <- sqrt(mean(res^2))
RMSE1
## [1] 4.274423

we can notice that we are getting the same result in both of the cases.

Similarly we can calculate the RMSE for the other 2 models.

data_6$x15 <- 1.5 * data_6$x
res1 = data_6$y - data_6$x15
RMSE2 <- sqrt(mean(res1^2))
RMSE2
## [1] 4.017965
data_6$x2 <- 2 * data_6$x
res2 = data_6$y - data_6$x2
RMSE3 <- sqrt(mean(res2^2))
RMSE3
## [1] 4.300501

We can notice that the RMSE for y=x is \(4.274\), y = 1.5x \(4.018\) and for y = 2x is \(4.3\). We can notice that the smallest error is \(4.018\) for y=1.5x meaning that this is the best model.

We can check this result using the function lm.

model <- lm(formula = y ~ x, data = data_6)
summary(model)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = y ~ x, data = data_6)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -15.3779  -2.7175  -0.0083   2.7586  16.6316 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)  0.01525    0.04018   0.379    0.704    
## x            1.48756    0.01343 110.772   <2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 4.018 on 9998 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.551,  Adjusted R-squared:  0.551 
## F-statistic: 1.227e+04 on 1 and 9998 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

The fitted model this function returns is y = 0.015 + 1.49x which is similar to the model y = 1.5x we used.

Exercise 2

Use the red-wine data set to build a regression model associating quality value of red wines with other measured features. There’s some additional information about the features in this supplementary file. You can use standard pre-implemented tools such as lm() in R for model fitting. Build the model iteratively by adding one feature at a time and retain features based on regression coefficient p-values(eg using a p-value threshold 0.05). Report the model building process and intermediate results. Interpret the included variables and corresponding coefficients of the final model. Report the adjusted R-squared and RMSE score.

Solution:

The wine data set contains 12 continuous features:

  • fixed acidity
  • volatile acidity
  • citric acid
  • residual sugar
  • chlorides
  • free sulfur dioxide
  • total sulfur dioxide
  • density
  • pH
  • sulphates
  • alcohol
  • quality

where the quality of the wine is the target variable.

We can plot and visualize the histogram of the quality so we can get a better sense of the distribution of this feature. we can notice that the distribution resembles like a normal distribution.

wine <- fread("C:/Users/Arsovska/Desktop/winequality-csv.csv")

# Plot the histogram

    fill = I("blue"), col = I("red"), alpha = I(0.5))

# Check the number of unique values

From the correlation matrix we can notice that quality has high correlation with alcohol. Many of the features have high correlation (for example the value of the correlation between density and fixed.acidity is 0.668) which can be a problem if we include them in the model because R will not be able to make a difference about the feature’s contribution.

Because quality has highest correlation with alcohol we can create the model first with this feature.

model1 <- lm(quality ~ alcohol, data = wine)

Exercise 3

Use the iris data set for testing differences of means with a t-test. First present your hypothesis (what are you going to check with the t-test). For formulating the hypothesis you need to choose a feature and two different flower types (ie Virginica, Setosa - you can choose the pair yourself). Then you can check whether the feature means of 2 different Iris flowers differ from each other with a pre-implemented t-test method.

Next, recreate this calculation by implementing two-sample t-test yourself. To do that, first calculate the t-statistic (you can find the formula online or from the lecture slides). Then use the distribution function of t-distribution to convert the t-statistic to p-value. Are the two classes means different (p-value)? Interpret and explain all steps and answers.

Present a visual illustration that would support your conclusion (plot the distributions for example).

Solution:

The T test is a parametric method which is appropriate for examining the difference between the means of 2 features.

This test asks whether a difference between two groups’ averages is unlikely to have occurred because of random chance in sample selection. A difference is more likely to be meaningful and “real” if:

  • the difference between the averages is large,
  • the sample size is large, and
  • responses are consistently close to the average values and not widely spread out (the standard deviation is low).

The t-test’s statistical significance and the t-test’s effect size are the two primary outputs of the t-test. Statistical significance indicates whether the difference between sample averages is likely to represent an actual difference between populations, and the effect size indicates whether that difference is large enough to be practically meaningful.

The iris data set contains 3 classes of 50 instances each, where each class refers to a type of iris plant. The attributes in this data set are the sepal length (cm), the sepal width (cm), the petal length (cm), the petal width (cm) and the species of the flower (Setosa, Versicolour and Virginica).

First we can create a box plot which will compare the sepal length and the distributions. Checking the form of the distribution is also important because the test assumes that the sampling distribution is approximately normal.

library(ggplot2)
attach(iris)
boxplot(iris$Sepal.Length ~ iris$Species, ylab = "Sepal Length (cm)", main = "Comparison of Sepal's Length")

ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length)) + geom_density(aes(group = Species, colour = Species, 
    fill = Species), alpha = 0.3) + ggtitle("Sepal's Length Distribution")

From the box plot we can notice that the sepal length seems to increase from setosa to versicolor to virginica. To comfirm this we can calculate the mean sepal length for each species.

tapply(iris$Sepal.Length, iris$Species, mean)
##     setosa versicolor  virginica 
##      5.006      5.936      6.588

Then we state the null and the hypothesis. The null hypothesis states that the mean of the Setosa’s sepal length is same as the Virginica sepal’s length. The alternative hypothesis is that they are different.

We can choose the significance level to be 0.05. For computing the two-sided T test we can use the command t.test in R.

t.test(iris$Sepal.Length[iris$Species == "setosa"], iris$Sepal.Length[iris$Species == 
    "virginica"])
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  iris$Sepal.Length[iris$Species == "setosa"] and iris$Sepal.Length[iris$Species == "virginica"]
## t = -15.386, df = 76.516, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -1.78676 -1.37724
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##     5.006     6.588

If we analyze the results from this test we can notice that the t value is different from 0 and the p value is smaller then 0.05 we can reject the null hypothesis and we can conclude that the there is a significant difference in sepal length. Sepals of species Virginica are on average 1.6 cm longer than sepals of species Setosa.

Similarly we can choose the feature Sepal width and plot the box plot and the distribution.

boxplot(iris$Sepal.Width ~ iris$Species, ylab = "Sepal Width (cm)", main = "Comparison of Sepal's Width")

We can state the null hypothesis that the means of the sepal’s width are same and the alternative hypothesis that they are the same. We can calculate the pairwise T test which will compare the width of the sepals for all species.

pairwise.t.test(iris$Sepal.Width, iris$Species)

From the results we can reject the null hypothesis. The p-values between all comparison groups are smaller then 0.05 which means that the sepal widths between all groups are statistically different from each other with Setosa sepal widths the largest and Virginica are the smallest.

Using the formula for the t value, the p value and the degrees of freedom we can recreate the 2 sample T test that compares the length of the sepals for the species setosa and virginica.

# Average values
tapply(iris$Sepal.Length, iris$Species, mean)
##     setosa versicolor  virginica 
##      5.006      5.936      6.588
t.test2 <- function(m1, m2, s1, s2, n1, n2, m0 = 0, equal.variance = FALSE) {
    if (equal.variance == FALSE) {
        se <- sqrt((s1^2/n1) + (s2^2/n2))
        # welch-satterthwaite df
        df <- ((s1^2/n1 + s2^2/n2)^2)/((s1^2/n1)^2/(n1 - 1) + (s2^2/n2)^2/(n2 - 
            1))
    }
    t <- (m1 - m2 - m0)/se
    dat <- c(df, m1 - m2, se, t, 2 * pt(-abs(t), df))
    names(dat) <- c("Degrees of freedom", "Difference of means", "Std Error", 
        "t", "p-value")
    return(dat)
}
a <- subset(iris, iris$Species == "setosa")
b <- subset(iris, iris$Species == "virginica")
t.test2(mean(a$Sepal.Length), mean(b$Sepal.Length), sd(a$Sepal.Length), sd(b$Sepal.Length), 
    50, 50)
##  Degrees of freedom Difference of means           Std Error 
##        7.651587e+01       -1.582000e+00        1.028194e-01 
##                   t             p-value 
##       -1.538620e+01        3.966867e-25

The returned values are:

  • degrees of freedom: \(76.51\)
  • t value: \(- 15.386\)
  • p value: \(3.966867e-25\)

Solution:

I tried to solve this assignment in 2 ways: using linear regression and random forest.

  • Random Forest

Random forest is an ensemble learning method that operates by constructing a multitude of decision trees at training time and outputting the class that is the mode of the classes (classification) or mean prediction (regression) of the individual trees. In R we can use the library randomForest/

First we can load the train data and split it (The test data does not contain the target variable so this step is needed for checking the accuracy of the algorithm. The provided test data will be used later).

DataFrame <- fread("C:/Users/Arsovska/Documents/train.csv")

Exercise 7

Try ridge and lasso regressions for model 4 from task 4 and add the resulting RMSE of training and test set on the plot generated in task 4. Explain in general terms what do ridge and lasso regression do. Then interpret the RMSE outcomes.

Solution:

When we are dealing with large number of parameters, it is needed to penalize some of them because they should have little effect compared to the others. Ridge and Lasso are regularization techniques that work by penalizing the magnitude of coefficients of features along with minimizing the error between predicted and actual observations.Ridge regression can’t zero out coefficients and we either end up including all the coefficients in the model, or none of them. In contrast, lasso does both parameter shrinkage and variable selection automatically.

Ridge uses L2 regression, where as lasso uses L1. In L2 regression, the penalty is the sum of the squares of the coefficients and for L1, it’s the sum of the absolute values of the coefficients. It’s a shrinkage towards zero using an absolute value (L1 penalty) rather than a sum of squares(L2 penalty).

In R we can calculate this regression using the glmnet package.

xfactors <- model.matrix(price ~ carat + cut + color + clarity + depth + table + 
    x + y + z + CaratSq + DepthSq + Depthcub + Caratcub + xsq + ysq + zsq)[, 
    -1]
xx <- as.matrix(data.frame(xfactors))
y <- df.train$price
lasso <- glmnet(xx, y = price, alpha = 1)
plot(lasso, main = "Lasso regression")

ridge <- glmnet(xx, y = price, alpha = 0)
plot(ridge, main = "Ridge regression")

# make predictions Lasso train data
predict_lasso_train <- predict(lasso, xx, type = "link")
# summarize accuracy
mse_lasso_train <- mean((y - predict_lasso_train)^2)
print(sqrt(mse_lasso_train))
## [1] 1696.819
# make predictions Ridge train data
predict_ridge_train <- predict(ridge, xx, type = "link")
# summarize accuracy
mse_ridge_train <- mean((y - predict_ridge_train)^2)
print(sqrt(mse_ridge_train))
## [1] 3022.178
xfac <- model.matrix(price_test ~ carat_test + cut_test + color_test + clarity_test + 
    depth_test + table_test + x_test + y_test + z_test + CaratSq_t + DepthSq_t + 
    Caratcub_t + Depthcub_t + xsq_t + ysq_t + zsq_t)[, -1]

xx_test <- as.matrix(data.frame(xfac))

# make predictions Lasso test data
predict_lasso_test <- predict(lasso, xx_test, type = "link")
mse_lasso_test <- mean((y_test - predict_lasso_test)^2)

# make predictions Ridge train data

mse_ridge_test <- mean((y_test - predict_ridge_test)^2)
